WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.000
Second Inaugural Address by Abraham Lincoln. Read by John Greenman for LibriVox.org.

00:07.000 --> 00:20.000
Fellow-Countrymen: At this second appearing to take the oath of the Presidential office

00:20.000 --> 00:30.000
there is less occasion for an extended address than there was at the first.

00:30.000 --> 00:42.000
Then a statement somewhat in detail of a course to be pursued seemed fitting and proper.

00:42.000 --> 00:58.000
Now, at the expiration of four years, during which public declarations have been constantly called forth on every point and phase of the great contest

00:58.000 --> 01:08.000
which still absorbs the attention and engrosses the energies of the nation, little that is new could be presented.

01:08.000 --> 01:20.000
The progress of our arms, upon which all else chiefly depends, is as well known to the public as to myself,

01:20.000 --> 01:34.000
and it is, I trust, reasonably satisfactory and encouraging to all. With high hope for the future, no prediction in regard to it is ventured.

01:34.000 --> 01:46.000
On the occasion corresponding to this four years ago all thoughts were anxiously directed to an impending civil war.

01:46.000 --> 01:58.000
All dreaded it, all sought to avert it. While the inaugural address was being delivered from this place,

01:58.000 --> 02:12.000
devoted altogether to saving the Union without war, insurgent agents were in the city seeking to destroy it without war—

02:12.000 --> 02:25.000
seeking to dissolve the Union and divide effects by negotiation. Both parties deprecated war,

02:25.000 --> 02:40.000
but one of them would make war rather than let the nation survive, and the other would accept war rather than let it perish, and the war came.
